[Our thanks to Betty for this very thorough and useful report. CFIA manages
anthrax outbreaks in Canada. It is clear that the weather played a part in
this both in encouraging Spring grazing growth in a heavily contaminated
pasture in King George RM. And one could speculate that the park bison were
protected by the cooler weather until the high temperatures crashed their
innate resistance, when the ongoing level of exposure could not be
effectively handled and infection occured. It is unusual to see deaths more
than 8 days after vaccination. These were all beef cattle; with dairy cows
vaccination failures have been ascribed to similtaneous mastitis treatment
with antibiotics but that would not apply with beef cows. Such late deaths
occur but frankly it is not common.

If nothing else this is a good example of the frequency of widely dispersed
sporadic outbreaks in a region with a history of epidemics; and therefore
the importance of maintaining vaccination, at least until the true risk is
minimal. - Mod.MHJ]
